1
00:00:02,662 --> 00:00:30,375
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:32,143 --> 00:00:36,390
homage to the blessed, noble, and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:46,688 --> 00:00:53,960
Traditionally, that's of course a chant to the historical Buddha, or to all the Buddhas.

4
00:00:53,979 --> 00:00:58,286
But spiritually, we are recognizing the Buddha within ourselves.

5
00:01:00,527 --> 00:01:17,212
Today marks the beginning of the winter retreat and it's an opportunity for those of you who've been here to re-establish your commitment and energy and to put more effort into the practice.

6
00:01:17,533 --> 00:01:20,897
Not that you haven't been putting maximum effort into the practice.

7
00:01:22,960 --> 00:01:29,049
And for those of you who have just joined, obviously it is a special period.

8
00:01:34,007 --> 00:01:42,858
Now it seems to me that we can waste a lot of time if we are confused or not clear about the aim of meditation practice.

9
00:01:46,963 --> 00:01:57,356
As far as I'm concerned, the only thing that we can expect of a meditation period is to feel that we've honed the skills of meditation a bit more.

10
00:01:59,379 --> 00:02:01,382
If we join a practice

11
00:02:02,105 --> 00:02:13,336
with the idea that we're going to achieve something, no matter what it is, even at a mundane level of a calm and peaceful mind, to rid ourselves of some peculiar neuroses.

12
00:02:14,117 --> 00:02:22,967
Even at that level, we immediately put pressure on ourselves, immediately put an ego idea of what the meditation is concerned with.

13
00:02:24,750 --> 00:02:30,036
So the first thing to do is to banish completely all aims and objectives.

14
00:02:31,669 --> 00:02:34,894
In so doing, we're then left, as it were, in an open space.

15
00:02:35,794 --> 00:02:44,506
And in that open space, we can perceive, perhaps, what the true intention of our meditation should be.

16
00:02:45,546 --> 00:02:53,295
And this is expressed by the Buddha in the Satipatthana discourse, the discourse on how to establish mindfulness.

17
00:02:53,316 --> 00:02:58,081
All he asks us to do is to be aware.

18
00:02:59,968 --> 00:03:04,754
And he uses three words to give us the idea of what this awareness might be.

19
00:03:05,415 --> 00:03:09,501
Atapi, sampajano, satima.

20
00:03:09,520 --> 00:03:14,407
Now atapi comes from the root word tapos, which means fire.

21
00:03:15,568 --> 00:03:15,889
Fire.

22
00:03:16,751 --> 00:03:19,935
And it refers to the energy that we have to put into the practice.

23
00:03:22,598 --> 00:03:28,926
If at any time we're not putting energy into the practice, then we're not going to establish this right awareness.

24
00:03:29,548 --> 00:03:33,752
However, that energy can become easily corrupted.

25
00:03:34,854 --> 00:03:37,878
So we have to also be very clear as to what the energy is.

26
00:03:40,222 --> 00:03:43,105
In Zen, they put it in this wonderful paradoxical way.

27
00:03:43,167 --> 00:03:46,570
It's the effortless effort.

28
00:03:46,591 --> 00:03:49,314
So we have to discover what the effortless effort is.

29
00:03:50,796 --> 00:03:55,021
That effortless effort has to sustain sampajanjo.

30
00:03:58,605 --> 00:04:06,955
Sampajanjo's root word is this ñ which comes right through our civilization in words like to know.

31
00:04:06,975 --> 00:04:10,179
The kn goes right back to that ñ, right?

32
00:04:10,219 --> 00:04:11,700
It comes through the Latin to us.

33
00:04:12,481 --> 00:04:14,104
And the root word is to know.

34
00:04:14,978 --> 00:04:19,343
And the suffix, the prefix, pa, is a reinforcement.

35
00:04:19,442 --> 00:04:22,865
And it's referring to a particular type of knowing.

36
00:04:23,706 --> 00:04:25,009
And that knowing is panya.

37
00:04:25,369 --> 00:04:29,593
That knowing is intuitive insight.

38
00:04:29,613 --> 00:04:38,262
So we have to understand what is meant by an intuitive intelligence as opposed to every other intelligence we have.

39
00:04:38,283 --> 00:04:44,850
And the third one is satima, which has in it there the word sati, which is a state of awareness.

40
00:04:46,466 --> 00:04:50,052
Effort, intelligence, awareness.

41
00:04:50,973 --> 00:04:56,781
That's the composition of the meditative mind.

42
00:04:56,802 --> 00:04:59,805
So now, what is the quality of awareness?

43
00:05:00,827 --> 00:05:06,495
In its simplest form, it's just to know, just to be here, a sense of presence.

44
00:05:08,178 --> 00:05:10,601
However, even frogs have that.

45
00:05:11,694 --> 00:05:14,819
All beings have a sense of presence.

46
00:05:14,860 --> 00:05:19,526
It might not be a self-conscious presence, but they definitely have a sense of presence.

47
00:05:22,110 --> 00:05:23,130
It's part of consciousness.

48
00:05:23,271 --> 00:05:25,314
It's a quality of consciousness to be conscious.

49
00:05:26,136 --> 00:05:29,279
Even in sleep, there's a sense of presence.

50
00:05:29,300 --> 00:05:32,043
Somebody pulls the blanket over you when you're cold.

51
00:05:33,505 --> 00:05:35,509
Somebody wakes up when the bell goes off.

52
00:05:36,281 --> 00:05:43,735
So even in deepest sleep, there's some slight awareness going on.

53
00:05:43,754 --> 00:05:46,017
So if it were just awareness, it wouldn't do.

54
00:05:46,057 --> 00:05:55,113
That awareness has to be flavored with this intelligence.

55
00:05:55,134 --> 00:05:58,759
And the flavor of that intelligence is simply a question mark.

56
00:05:58,779 --> 00:06:00,062
It's a curiosity.

57
00:06:01,189 --> 00:06:23,062
If that curiosity has a word attached to it, if that curiosity has a goal attached to it, a sentence, anicca, dukkha, anatta, transiency, suffering, nibbana, if that question mark is corrupted by a question,

58
00:06:23,194 --> 00:06:31,627
then we immediately drop into a thinking mind, a mind which is distorted in some way by conceptual thinking.

59
00:06:33,550 --> 00:06:41,783
So somehow we have to raise that intelligence, we have to abstract it, we have to disembed it out of thought.

60
00:06:43,687 --> 00:06:44,528
Equally,

61
00:06:44,913 --> 00:06:57,129
If that state is coloured by an emotion and we presume that this intuition has something to do with a feeling, then that is also a similar mistake.

62
00:06:58,610 --> 00:07:07,242
Both of these things we now call intelligence what we normally mean by intelligence and what we normally mean now by emotional intelligence.

63
00:07:07,660 --> 00:07:19,411
Both of these types of intelligences are simply expressions of the original intelligence as it expresses itself through thought and emotion, and ultimately through the body.

64
00:07:20,132 --> 00:07:22,072
The body itself has an intelligence.

65
00:07:22,454 --> 00:07:23,375
We see it in athletes.

66
00:07:27,038 --> 00:07:34,764
So the business of meditation, the business of vipassana, is to first of all get to a point where we can actually practice vipassana.

67
00:07:34,879 --> 00:07:37,783
And that vipassana itself means to really see.

68
00:07:38,182 --> 00:07:41,386
The root word passati just means to see, to really see.

69
00:07:41,485 --> 00:07:45,389
So it's again referring to this insightfulness, this intelligence.

70
00:07:47,711 --> 00:08:03,908
And the effort we need is simply the effort to get to that level of consciousness, to get to that point where this purity of awareness with this lovely open question mark is allowed to exist, just to be.

71
00:08:04,968 --> 00:08:34,114
So whatever technique we employ in our meditation, doesn't matter what it is, whether it's the strict Mahasi thing about noting and walking slowly or view back in, flowing up and down the body or whatever skill, whatever technique you employ, it's always to do with getting ourselves into this completely open, spacious awareness which has this question mark, this curiosity about it.

72
00:08:37,485 --> 00:08:43,412
So the first thing is, when we sit, is to use some object, mainly the breath.

73
00:08:44,854 --> 00:08:47,115
And the reason we use the breath is because it's neutral.

74
00:08:47,336 --> 00:08:53,903
So it immediately drains away from the system any emotion which might be attached to a particular object.

75
00:08:55,384 --> 00:09:00,149
Watching a film is exciting, but watching the breath can be positively boring.

76
00:09:01,230 --> 00:09:03,712
There's nothing there, it's just the breath, just the sensations.

77
00:09:04,653 --> 00:09:07,256
By putting our mind just on the sensations,

78
00:09:07,809 --> 00:09:18,782
with no other intention than to feel sensations, experience sensations as sensations, then there arises a certain brightness in the mind.

79
00:09:20,024 --> 00:09:28,633
When that brightness awakens within us, find that position within yourself of an intelligent observation.

80
00:09:29,654 --> 00:09:32,738
And the closest image I have of that is of a child.

81
00:09:33,865 --> 00:09:38,370
When a child sees a bug they've never seen before, they fix on it, don't they?

82
00:09:38,389 --> 00:09:40,172
Their eyes just fixate on that bug.

83
00:09:40,552 --> 00:09:41,374
They stop still.

84
00:09:41,413 --> 00:09:43,816
There's an absolute silence comes upon them.

85
00:09:43,836 --> 00:09:44,636
And the mouth drops.

86
00:09:46,899 --> 00:09:54,708
The mouth dropping and the tongue stopping is a sign that the intellectual, the thinking faculty has stopped.

87
00:09:54,729 --> 00:10:00,294
If you watch yourself very closely, whenever you're thinking, there's always some little vibrations on the tongue.

88
00:10:01,708 --> 00:10:12,626
So when the tongue is still and the jaw drops, and the eyes become still, then this intelligence begins to appear.

89
00:10:13,908 --> 00:10:21,861
In your meditation, you see, the teeth should be separate because the jaw should be relaxed.

90
00:10:21,881 --> 00:10:23,544
The lips are closed, but the jaw is relaxed.

91
00:10:27,591 --> 00:10:28,172
So,

92
00:10:30,143 --> 00:10:33,589
Getting into that position, we need an effort to get ourselves there.

93
00:10:34,490 --> 00:10:40,278
And that effort is simply the effort to keep bringing that mind back into this position.

94
00:10:42,283 --> 00:10:48,732
Now, in this particular technique of the Mahasi, for instance, this noting word is used.

95
00:10:48,753 --> 00:10:50,034
It's a very skillful way.

96
00:10:50,336 --> 00:10:53,080
Remember, the Mahasi was a scholar.

97
00:10:53,379 --> 00:11:13,717
In fact, he was what was called the questioner at the great meeting of 1956 to celebrate 2,500 years, where many of the scholars and monks and people like that came to Rangoon, where they built a special building that looked like the original cave.

98
00:11:14,609 --> 00:11:21,664
where the first council was convened after the Buddha's death, and there they agreed upon the different scriptures.

99
00:11:21,904 --> 00:11:26,315
Most of it, of course, was just an agreement of what was already agreed upon.

100
00:11:26,615 --> 00:11:29,763
But it was an occasion where certain things were discussed.

101
00:11:30,344 --> 00:11:33,090
And he was the so-called questioner.

102
00:11:33,070 --> 00:11:38,437
So his standing in the Buddhist community, the Theravada Buddhist community, was second to none.

103
00:11:38,457 --> 00:11:40,081
He was considered to be a scholar.

104
00:11:40,822 --> 00:11:46,410
Now the problem with any people who live in their head is in fact that they live in their head.

105
00:11:47,251 --> 00:11:54,082
So this technique that he devised was especially apt for people who get caught up in thought.

106
00:11:55,192 --> 00:11:59,438
Our particular culture definitely gets us caught up in thought.

107
00:12:00,341 --> 00:12:17,285
So, by reducing the whole of thought to a single word, rising, falling, looking, stretching, tasting, by reducing thought to a single word, it immediately cuts out this whole proliferation of thought around an object.

108
00:12:18,768 --> 00:12:23,135
So using a word like that can be very skillful.

109
00:12:23,436 --> 00:12:29,427
So you bring yourself back, rising, falling, rising, falling.

110
00:12:29,447 --> 00:12:42,210
Now, if at the first time, as we begin to meditate, there is this effort to just bring the mind back, something takes us away, if we are aggressive towards that something,

111
00:12:42,595 --> 00:12:51,323
If we push it away, if we see it as a nuisance to our meditation, then we're simply putting aggression, more aggression, into the system.

112
00:12:52,645 --> 00:13:01,595
So we have to note what that is, the wandering mind, whatever the content is, worrying, thinking, dreaming, whatever it is, we just note it.

113
00:13:02,135 --> 00:13:03,937
It's a careful observation of that.

114
00:13:04,258 --> 00:13:05,839
Remember, that's a memory of a thought.

115
00:13:06,240 --> 00:13:07,541
A memory of a thought.

116
00:13:08,282 --> 00:13:11,184
And then we just guide our attention back to the breath.

117
00:13:12,211 --> 00:13:16,057
This action of bringing the attention back to the breath is an act of will.

118
00:13:17,400 --> 00:13:18,923
Will is what conditions us.

119
00:13:19,565 --> 00:13:26,879
Every time we make the effort to just gently bring that breath, that attention back to the breath, it's conditioning the mind to be still.

120
00:13:28,020 --> 00:13:32,789
So the first part of any meditation is just bringing the mind to rest upon an object.

121
00:13:33,652 --> 00:13:34,894
We use mainly the breath.

122
00:13:35,953 --> 00:13:36,916
That's your first state.

123
00:13:37,736 --> 00:13:43,426
Once you're there, once you've done that, you see, you then have just the word and just the object.

124
00:13:44,567 --> 00:13:55,764
Now, as you begin to keep saying the word and keep going into the object, there comes a feeling of being fixed on the object, that you can't move off the object.

125
00:13:55,825 --> 00:13:57,607
Nothing can take you from it.

126
00:13:58,027 --> 00:14:08,024
Even when a thought comes, even when a sound comes, there'll be a recognition of hearing and then immediate return to the breath.

127
00:14:10,006 --> 00:14:15,917
Now at that point, the concentration has risen to the level of what we call first jhāna.

128
00:14:17,010 --> 00:14:20,917
What we mean by an absorption state is that the mind is still on the object.

129
00:14:21,658 --> 00:14:32,335
The difference between this sort of concentration and a concentration that we might get in jhana, the absorptions, is that what we want from jhana is a beautiful state of mind.

130
00:14:33,336 --> 00:14:41,128
What we want from jhana is to increase that beautiful state of mind and turn ourselves into glorious charismatics.

131
00:14:42,037 --> 00:14:45,769
However, the purpose of insight meditation is not that.

132
00:14:45,809 --> 00:14:51,388
It's to actually begin to see where we're causing ourselves problems.

133
00:14:52,330 --> 00:15:00,701
Remember the Buddha reduced the whole of his teachings to three words in the Pali, dukkha, dukkha nirodha, suffering and the end of suffering.

134
00:15:00,880 --> 00:15:01,861
It's as simple as that.

135
00:15:02,322 --> 00:15:13,056
So what we're concerned with ultimately in our meditation is to find out where does suffering arise, who's causing suffering, is there a who that causes suffering, etc., etc.

136
00:15:12,335 --> 00:15:13,056
?

137
00:15:13,457 --> 00:15:22,461
So, drawing our mind to this point where the word is still keeping us on the breath, we can say to ourselves, this concentration is good.

138
00:15:24,004 --> 00:15:27,855
So we can, at that point, congratulate ourselves and feel good about it.

139
00:15:28,712 --> 00:15:43,854
At that point, we then keep centering in on the breath, still able to observe anything which arises, be it a feeling in the body, an emotion, a thought, whatever it is, we still keep going and we still keep coming back to the breath.

140
00:15:45,255 --> 00:15:53,606
And there comes a point where the concentration is so blocked into the present moment that there's no time for words.

141
00:15:54,379 --> 00:15:56,721
Thought is always an afterthought.

142
00:15:56,741 --> 00:16:00,505
In that blocking into the present moment, the thinking mind simply stops.

143
00:16:01,788 --> 00:16:02,729
That's vipassana.

144
00:16:04,791 --> 00:16:07,472
That's the point where true insight will arise for us.

145
00:16:08,354 --> 00:16:11,577
Our whole practice is to bring ourselves to that point.

146
00:16:12,399 --> 00:16:16,482
The whole of our effort is just to bring ourselves to that point.

147
00:16:16,503 --> 00:16:16,883
That's all.

148
00:16:19,085 --> 00:16:23,610
That's why the Buddha insists on this idea of awareness in the present moment.

149
00:16:24,534 --> 00:16:29,042
In the present moment, there's no time for the mind to think about the present moment.

150
00:16:29,565 --> 00:16:30,731
It's in the present moment.

151
00:16:31,942 --> 00:16:41,595
Being in the present moment, that intelligence now, as it were, sheds off any conceptual thinking and is able to directly experience what's actually going on.

152
00:16:41,615 --> 00:16:49,304
And it's in those moments that some small insight can arise concerning these three characteristics of existence.

153
00:16:50,046 --> 00:16:51,207
The fact of transiency.

154
00:16:51,528 --> 00:16:54,672
The fact that everything is not self.

155
00:16:55,813 --> 00:17:00,820
The fact that if I form a relationship with anything of me and mine, possession...

156
00:17:01,102 --> 00:17:06,108
identity, wanting, not wanting, some form of dissatisfaction will arise.

157
00:17:07,932 --> 00:17:14,319
These things, according to the Buddha, arise quite naturally to that intelligence once it gets into that position.

158
00:17:15,580 --> 00:17:25,473
These little insights are not sort of mind-blowing experiences, where you suddenly fling yourself up in the air and say, got it, eureka, like poor old Archimedes.

159
00:17:27,428 --> 00:17:30,875
These moments are just very simple, very obvious to the intelligence.

160
00:17:31,297 --> 00:17:32,559
You wouldn't think anything of them.

161
00:17:33,101 --> 00:17:43,125
But the effect slowly, over a period of time, is to shave away all that delusion and we find ourselves unbinding ourselves.

162
00:17:44,336 --> 00:17:50,385
All these opinions, definitions, all these needs and wants are bindings around us.

163
00:17:51,126 --> 00:17:56,836
So this cutting off, this loosening of the binding is the process of the enlightenment.

164
00:17:57,096 --> 00:18:04,607
That's why Nibbana is translated in one sense as unbinding, unshackling.

165
00:18:05,689 --> 00:18:13,280
That's why the Buddha says he's achieved the asankhatam chittam, which is the unconditioned mind, the unconditioned consciousness.

166
00:18:14,644 --> 00:18:21,838
It's a consciousness which is living in the world, fully in the world, but not caught up in the world.

167
00:18:21,858 --> 00:18:33,582
When you're in that state of pure vipassana, when you're there just watching, just able to be with it, you see, when you come out of that state, ask yourself, what were the qualities of that state?

168
00:18:34,220 --> 00:18:34,539
You see?

169
00:18:35,161 --> 00:18:37,344
Even though there was pain, were you suffering?

170
00:18:37,923 --> 00:18:43,310
Even though there was an emotional state which was painful, were you suffering?

171
00:18:43,330 --> 00:18:46,755
Even though there was great joy, were you excited?

172
00:18:47,715 --> 00:18:49,778
What was your relationship to what you were watching?

173
00:18:52,060 --> 00:19:01,392
So now, once we understand where we have to get to, then we have to, as it were, hone those skills to protect it.

174
00:19:03,025 --> 00:19:14,096
So if the first part of our period is just trying gently to bring ourselves back to this, we always have to be on guard for the armies of Mara.

175
00:19:14,115 --> 00:19:20,281
Now the first, the first attack is anything which is pleasurable.

176
00:19:20,301 --> 00:19:23,846
Now, when we say pleasure, is it pleasure that we want to get rid of?

177
00:19:24,446 --> 00:19:25,047
Definitely not.

178
00:19:26,568 --> 00:19:27,730
There's nothing wrong with pleasure.

179
00:19:28,510 --> 00:19:29,791
We all know it's very beautiful.

180
00:19:31,038 --> 00:19:37,946
Nobody would want to follow the spiritual practice of Buddhism if we had to ban cream cakes.

181
00:19:38,768 --> 00:19:39,608
It's not necessary.

182
00:19:41,010 --> 00:19:45,757
Our problem is not pleasure, but our relationship to pleasure.

183
00:19:45,777 --> 00:19:47,278
What is it we want from pleasure?

184
00:19:48,280 --> 00:19:57,011
Whether it be something quite basic, like porridge, or something wonderful, like love.

185
00:19:59,101 --> 00:20:02,483
Or something sublime, like some great spiritual joy.

186
00:20:03,384 --> 00:20:04,486
What is it we want from it, you see?

187
00:20:05,166 --> 00:20:07,828
We want happiness, don't we?

188
00:20:07,848 --> 00:20:08,569
We want happiness.

189
00:20:08,730 --> 00:20:09,770
We want to be happy.

190
00:20:10,791 --> 00:20:13,494
If we were always happy, we wouldn't meditate, would we?

191
00:20:14,355 --> 00:20:15,717
We'd just be perfectly happy.

192
00:20:16,758 --> 00:20:20,761
So our problem is, is that this search for happiness isn't working.

193
00:20:21,923 --> 00:20:26,307
We keep investing in all this stuff, and it just keeps letting us down.

194
00:20:29,594 --> 00:20:33,678
In terms of an investor on the stock market, he would think we're real fools.

195
00:20:34,739 --> 00:20:40,365
To put any investment at all in the joys of life, knowing full well that you can't trust them at all.

196
00:20:41,125 --> 00:20:43,067
You can't even trust human beings.

197
00:20:44,969 --> 00:20:51,296
The last thing we would want to put our trust in for our personal happiness is another human being.

198
00:20:51,997 --> 00:20:52,537
They're terrible.

199
00:20:54,598 --> 00:20:55,259
They leave you.

200
00:20:56,681 --> 00:20:58,403
They do awful things to you.

201
00:20:59,327 --> 00:21:00,990
Then they get sick and they die.

202
00:21:01,029 --> 00:21:05,394
They can just leave you utterly bereft.

203
00:21:05,414 --> 00:21:12,022
So the last thing we need to find this absolute comfort in is anything to do with a phenomenal world.

204
00:21:14,266 --> 00:21:16,909
So therefore we have to, as it were, come off the drug.

205
00:21:17,368 --> 00:21:18,730
Come off the drug of pleasure.

206
00:21:20,313 --> 00:21:23,817
But first of all we have to be convinced that in fact pleasure is a drug.

207
00:21:24,926 --> 00:21:28,971
We have to see that our addiction is taking us to more and more suffering.

208
00:21:29,731 --> 00:21:35,497
Now, the one time of the day when you can make this very plain to yourself is when you're eating.

209
00:21:36,657 --> 00:21:37,499
Take it slowly.

210
00:21:38,039 --> 00:21:40,201
Sit there before the food.

211
00:21:40,842 --> 00:21:41,823
Contact the body.

212
00:21:42,483 --> 00:21:43,944
Contact the feeling of hunger.

213
00:21:45,886 --> 00:21:49,611
Know that somewhere mixed in that is the desire to find happiness.

214
00:21:49,990 --> 00:21:50,751
See, that's the greed.

215
00:21:51,593 --> 00:21:54,174
I'm going to really enjoy this.

216
00:21:56,990 --> 00:21:59,934
Sausage, mash and beans.

217
00:22:04,063 --> 00:22:05,565
Can't think of anything more delightful.

218
00:22:07,608 --> 00:22:11,275
There's this little voice saying, this is going to be really good.

219
00:22:15,142 --> 00:22:20,652
So, once it's there, using that noting word, if it works for you,

220
00:22:21,002 --> 00:22:23,286
Very slowly, see, lift up the food.

221
00:22:23,886 --> 00:22:26,670
Now when it hits the tongue, what do we have, you see?

222
00:22:26,809 --> 00:22:27,510
We have pleasure.

223
00:22:28,051 --> 00:22:32,998
At the physical base, we have the tongue telling us what a wonderful thing this is.

224
00:22:34,519 --> 00:22:43,010
Now when I say we have pleasure, this pleasure is just sensations which are being interpreted by the mind as something pleasurable.

225
00:22:44,746 --> 00:22:54,156
If you were one of those very unfortunate persons who didn't like sausage, mash and beans, it would not be perceived as something pleasurable.

226
00:22:55,499 --> 00:22:59,844
This idea of pleasurable is not within the sausage, mash and beans.

227
00:23:00,345 --> 00:23:04,630
The idea of what is pleasurable and worthy of enjoyment is in the head.

228
00:23:05,391 --> 00:23:09,015
It's in the way we have associated with this object.

229
00:23:10,192 --> 00:23:14,877
Taking our consciousness deep into the tongue, what do we find, you see?

230
00:23:15,519 --> 00:23:16,099
Just taste.

231
00:23:17,961 --> 00:23:21,125
Around it we've built this aura of enjoyment.

232
00:23:22,646 --> 00:23:27,031
We have to separate out the taste on the tongue from the aura of enjoyment.

233
00:23:27,092 --> 00:23:31,217
And in so doing, we're actually beginning to deconstruct the event.

234
00:23:32,057 --> 00:23:36,942
In deconstructing the event, we're also going to find that there's nobody enjoying it.

235
00:23:38,272 --> 00:23:46,183
One of the constant little techniques that the Buddha uses throughout the scripture is the technique of deconstructing.

236
00:23:46,304 --> 00:23:47,164
Deconstructing.

237
00:23:47,786 --> 00:23:49,288
He turns everything into lists.

238
00:23:49,488 --> 00:23:50,328
You've come across them.

239
00:23:50,388 --> 00:23:52,972
The five aggregates and the six sense bases.

240
00:23:52,992 --> 00:23:54,934
Everything has to be pulled apart.

241
00:23:55,556 --> 00:23:58,380
And he does that in order to take away the concept of wholeness.

242
00:23:58,819 --> 00:24:00,382
The concept of an entity.

243
00:24:01,644 --> 00:24:03,066
So you're here.

244
00:24:03,046 --> 00:24:03,686
Tasting.

245
00:24:04,367 --> 00:24:08,435
As you perceive the taste, you see that there's an emotion around it.

246
00:24:09,336 --> 00:24:13,263
Now what we have to see is what is our relationship to that state.

247
00:24:15,969 --> 00:24:16,229
You see?

248
00:24:16,931 --> 00:24:19,434
What is the relationship we have to that state?

249
00:24:20,106 --> 00:24:22,569
And that relationship is one of desire.

250
00:24:22,589 --> 00:24:25,973
That relationship is one of wanting to be happy right there.

251
00:24:27,295 --> 00:24:32,000
If we can catch that movement, then we're catching what the Buddha calls tanha.

252
00:24:32,662 --> 00:24:35,285
It's rather heavily translated as craving.

253
00:24:35,585 --> 00:24:41,372
But it's that desire of consciousness, desire to find happiness in sensual pleasure.

254
00:24:42,684 --> 00:24:48,290
If we can stay above all that, if we can stay above all that, see, that's the vipassana mind.

255
00:24:48,330 --> 00:25:09,115
If we can stay above all that and we can slowly as we eat allow this greed to just pass away because we're not feeding the greed and we reduce ourselves simply to the food and the pleasure it brings in the heart, you see, then we're discovering a way of being with pleasure in that non-indulgent way.

256
00:25:11,086 --> 00:25:16,431
If we indulge in pleasure, any time, there will always be a hangover.

257
00:25:17,211 --> 00:25:19,193
We think we only get hangovers when we get drunk.

258
00:25:19,834 --> 00:25:22,376
But hangovers come any time you have pleasure.

259
00:25:22,636 --> 00:25:23,557
We've got to catch that.

260
00:25:23,597 --> 00:25:24,578
We've got to see that.

261
00:25:24,618 --> 00:25:29,002
We've got to see that pleasure, that indulgence in pleasure, doesn't deliver.

262
00:25:29,242 --> 00:25:30,084
We've actually got to see it.

263
00:25:31,744 --> 00:25:39,792
When we've indulged in pleasure, become attached to pleasure, the problem is afterwards, the frustration of not getting it when you want.

264
00:25:41,646 --> 00:25:48,375
The underlying fear that exists, that sub-exists all pleasure, that you might never get it again.

265
00:25:50,517 --> 00:25:53,460
These two things, the grief at the loss of pleasure.

266
00:25:53,961 --> 00:26:04,031
If you take any of your sense bases, your eyes for instance, the amount of pleasure and joy we get from our eyes, you've only got to imagine one moment slowly going blind.

267
00:26:05,634 --> 00:26:06,836
Where does the suffering come from?

268
00:26:07,175 --> 00:26:08,176
Are the eyes suffering?

269
00:26:10,115 --> 00:26:10,955
Where's the pain?

270
00:26:10,996 --> 00:26:12,317
Where's the despair coming from?

271
00:26:13,238 --> 00:26:14,740
It's coming from that identity.

272
00:26:14,759 --> 00:26:18,483
It's coming from that indulgence, association.

273
00:26:18,503 --> 00:26:23,388
It's coming from that addiction to pleasure as a place where we're going to be happy.

274
00:26:24,170 --> 00:26:36,762
So part of our process of enlightenment is to unshackle ourselves of the idea that we can find happiness in the sensual, pleasurable, even in the spiritual world of high absorptions.

275
00:26:38,363 --> 00:26:42,646
And yet we also mustn't make the mistake that we have to kill the pleasure.

276
00:26:43,307 --> 00:26:44,548
It's nothing to do with pleasure.

277
00:26:45,829 --> 00:26:49,753
We often hear that quote from the Bible, money is the root of evil.

278
00:26:49,773 --> 00:26:55,220
But the real quote from the Bible is quite correctly, it's the love of money which is the root of all evil.

279
00:26:55,240 --> 00:26:57,741
So it's the love of things which is causing our problems.

280
00:26:59,663 --> 00:27:04,489
So putting pleasure aside, we now have to deal with all those things which are horrible.

281
00:27:06,645 --> 00:27:17,769
When something like aversion comes up, and in a meditation, probably boredom, something like that, you have to be very careful not to listen to these things.

282
00:27:18,289 --> 00:27:20,773
Boredom will always tell you to seek distraction.

283
00:27:21,255 --> 00:27:22,316
Try another technique.

284
00:27:22,576 --> 00:27:24,439
Go do some walking meditation.

285
00:27:25,560 --> 00:27:26,623
I need to stretch myself.

286
00:27:26,702 --> 00:27:28,486
I'll walk around the property and look at the flowers.

287
00:27:29,267 --> 00:27:31,570
It'll always tell you to go and do something which makes you happy.

288
00:27:32,070 --> 00:27:33,492
But that's not the cure to boredom.

289
00:27:33,953 --> 00:27:35,936
Boredom is cured through repetition.

290
00:27:36,898 --> 00:27:46,153
I'm sure you've all experienced during your learning days where you've got bored with something, but because you've kept at it, then the interest again arises naturally.

291
00:27:47,095 --> 00:27:47,394
Yes?

292
00:27:47,736 --> 00:27:48,076
Correct?

293
00:27:48,616 --> 00:27:48,977
Definitely.

294
00:27:50,019 --> 00:28:04,936
So it's a case of observing the boredom, feeling the boredom, experiencing the boredom as boredom, seeing how we relate to boredom, how we want to escape it, thinking that distraction will bring the end of boredom.

295
00:28:04,957 --> 00:28:05,257
You see?

296
00:28:06,317 --> 00:28:10,903
All that has to be seen and we have to wait patiently for the boredom to dissipate.

297
00:28:12,125 --> 00:28:14,367
All negative states come to rest.

298
00:28:15,326 --> 00:28:19,311
Interestingly enough, in the scriptures the Buddha never talks about going from hatred to love.

299
00:28:19,632 --> 00:28:22,775
He always talks about going from hatred to non-hatred.

300
00:28:23,516 --> 00:28:27,099
First of all, that turbulence has to be allowed to come to rest.

301
00:28:27,520 --> 00:28:30,124
Only then is it transformed into its opposite.

302
00:28:30,785 --> 00:28:36,911
So just as much as we were bored, don't be surprised if the same amount of energy arises as interest.

303
00:28:38,653 --> 00:28:40,895
It's just turning over itself.

304
00:28:43,946 --> 00:28:59,262
When it comes to sloth and torpor, you see, now it seems to me that a meditator needs no more than six hours per night.

305
00:28:59,282 --> 00:29:01,424
And in fact should do with more like five and a half.

306
00:29:02,365 --> 00:29:05,849
We sleep in one and three hour, one and three quarter hour cycles.

307
00:29:07,671 --> 00:29:08,511
I mean, what are we doing?

308
00:29:09,693 --> 00:29:10,534
Are we digging roads?

309
00:29:10,574 --> 00:29:13,076
Does the body need vast amounts of rest?

310
00:29:13,563 --> 00:29:14,523
Are we stressed?

311
00:29:14,584 --> 00:29:16,385
Are people rushing at us all over the place?

312
00:29:16,445 --> 00:29:17,247
Do this, do that?

313
00:29:17,446 --> 00:29:19,888
Are we into production targets?

314
00:29:19,909 --> 00:29:24,433
Are our minds being caught up in all sorts of figures and thoughts and plans?

315
00:29:25,234 --> 00:29:26,236
We're completely relaxed.

316
00:29:26,736 --> 00:29:33,803
So therefore, a meditator should say to themselves, if I'm sleeping more than five and a half hours, this may very well be sloth.

317
00:29:35,585 --> 00:29:39,108
And if it reaches eight, then it's profoundly disgusting.

318
00:29:41,191 --> 00:29:43,553
Only dogs sleep eight hours a day.

319
00:29:46,199 --> 00:29:55,189
So we have to awaken, you see, we have to lift up that energy, that physical energy, to match the mental energy that we need in order to make these sorts of efforts.

320
00:29:57,352 --> 00:30:02,857
So once you've decided that enough's enough, any time tiredness comes, don't be fooled by it.

321
00:30:03,858 --> 00:30:07,083
You know these little voices that say just a ten minute kip will do you very good here.

322
00:30:08,724 --> 00:30:09,605
Lift yourself up.

323
00:30:10,227 --> 00:30:12,409
Refuse to be annihilated.

324
00:30:12,557 --> 00:30:16,161
Refuse to be dominated by a feeling of sloth and torpor.

325
00:30:17,061 --> 00:30:18,202
Don't call it tiredness.

326
00:30:18,403 --> 00:30:18,864
You've had it.

327
00:30:19,284 --> 00:30:20,345
Call it sloth and torpor.

328
00:30:21,306 --> 00:30:24,808
And lift yourself up and make yourself walk gently.

329
00:30:24,989 --> 00:30:25,650
Walk with it.

330
00:30:25,809 --> 00:30:26,750
Make it your object.

331
00:30:28,172 --> 00:30:30,173
What are the feelings of sloth and torpor?

332
00:30:30,433 --> 00:30:31,474
Where do they arise?

333
00:30:31,875 --> 00:30:34,356
Do you feel sloth and torpor at the end of your fingers?

334
00:30:35,298 --> 00:30:37,079
Has your nose ever felt torporous?

335
00:30:38,721 --> 00:30:39,942
Where does it arise?

336
00:30:40,242 --> 00:30:41,703
Keep searching for it.

337
00:30:42,510 --> 00:30:45,055
Keep an objective view of it.

338
00:30:45,556 --> 00:30:47,720
See it as something interesting to explore.

339
00:30:48,902 --> 00:30:58,818
Don't be surprised if this sloth and torpor begin to evaporate and suddenly you find yourself with a very clear, pure energy.

340
00:31:00,161 --> 00:31:01,002
Because that's the opposite.

341
00:31:02,726 --> 00:31:08,214
If you find yourself restless, jumping about, be careful not to

342
00:31:08,431 --> 00:31:12,096
Obey these little commands that come from within us.

343
00:31:12,676 --> 00:31:14,019
Move, do this, do that.

344
00:31:14,980 --> 00:31:17,944
Where restlessness wants you to move, stay absolutely still.

345
00:31:18,226 --> 00:31:18,685
Refuse.

346
00:31:19,126 --> 00:31:20,048
Just refuse to move.

347
00:31:22,131 --> 00:31:32,006
If, for instance, you feel very restless before you go to sleep, one of the best tricks is to get yourself into a comfortable position and refuse to move.

348
00:31:33,208 --> 00:31:36,732
It may be agony for a little while, but then the energy just turns.

349
00:31:37,404 --> 00:31:41,551
So it's a case of accepting that these are just energy forms.

350
00:31:41,932 --> 00:31:43,694
We have to stop giving them names.

351
00:31:43,736 --> 00:31:45,778
We have to stop giving them some sort of credence.

352
00:31:46,420 --> 00:31:50,105
Stop giving them some sort of power over us.

353
00:31:50,906 --> 00:31:55,776
And we do that by just gently refusing to obey them.

354
00:31:55,796 --> 00:31:57,898
So when restlessness comes, be still with it.

355
00:31:58,820 --> 00:31:59,882
Relax around it.

356
00:32:01,625 --> 00:32:02,686
Refuse to move.

357
00:32:10,615 --> 00:32:11,615
And finally, doubt.

358
00:32:13,176 --> 00:32:14,499
So doubt is insidious.

359
00:32:15,500 --> 00:32:28,412
And the one way to overcome doubt is just to create, shall we say, an area where there'll be just a putting of confidence into the practice, a putting of confidence into ourselves.

360
00:32:29,512 --> 00:32:34,897
And when doubt comes, when there's some sort of, I can't do it, that's one of the big ones, isn't it?

361
00:32:34,917 --> 00:32:35,939
I can't do it, you see.

362
00:32:36,380 --> 00:32:38,240
Make that the object of your awareness.

363
00:32:39,782 --> 00:32:39,863
See?

364
00:32:40,567 --> 00:32:43,391
Don't let anything grab us.

365
00:32:44,951 --> 00:32:48,935
As soon as we find ourselves caught up in something, push it away, push it away.

366
00:32:51,397 --> 00:32:54,882
Observe it, experience it as an object.

367
00:32:55,982 --> 00:32:57,064
Don't get caught up in it.

368
00:32:58,986 --> 00:33:05,071
This sceptical doubt is often based on a fear of commitment.

369
00:33:05,092 --> 00:33:08,634
It's often based on a feeling of low self-esteem.

370
00:33:09,053 --> 00:33:14,859
This is not the same as what we might call honest doubt, the doubt that the Buddha asks us to have towards his teaching.

371
00:33:15,641 --> 00:33:17,563
That's a sense of, is it true?

372
00:33:17,782 --> 00:33:20,465
And then a real desire to investigate.

373
00:33:21,586 --> 00:33:23,650
That's the wonder of a philosopher.

374
00:33:25,372 --> 00:33:31,157
And that's the mood that we have to engender within us, which is one of the factors of enlightenment.

375
00:33:33,080 --> 00:33:36,984
Our meditation should be

376
00:33:38,720 --> 00:33:41,664
Gently saturated with joy.

377
00:33:44,147 --> 00:33:48,355
And that gentle saturation is caused by piti.

378
00:33:50,278 --> 00:33:57,048
Piti translates as joy, bliss, all those sorts of words.

379
00:33:57,449 --> 00:33:59,471
But it's far too strong for vipassana.

380
00:34:00,133 --> 00:34:04,239
That sort of thing is highly developed through these absorption states.

381
00:34:04,479 --> 00:34:07,443
But as far as vipassana is concerned, it's interest.

382
00:34:08,402 --> 00:34:10,585
Interest.

383
00:34:10,605 --> 00:34:15,728
I'm sure you remember times when you've been very interested in something.

384
00:34:15,748 --> 00:34:16,650
And it's been joyous.

385
00:34:18,472 --> 00:34:18,851
Correct.

386
00:34:19,913 --> 00:34:20,313
Interest.

387
00:34:21,554 --> 00:34:27,079
So this interest has to be, as it were, lifted by us out of our system.

388
00:34:27,119 --> 00:34:31,802
We have to bring up the interest, bring up the desire to want to know.

389
00:34:31,842 --> 00:34:33,684
That's the Gnostic path.

390
00:34:34,204 --> 00:34:36,027
That's the path of the scientist.

391
00:34:36,487 --> 00:34:37,768
They want to know.

392
00:34:38,322 --> 00:34:46,032
So this interest as it arises within us, you see, is a support to that intelligence.

393
00:34:50,737 --> 00:34:57,206
So we need to be able to cajole ourselves, to argue ourselves into a point that this is very interesting.

394
00:34:58,748 --> 00:35:06,016
And then you'll find that, of course, because the heart is joyous, everything will come up to support your meditation.

395
00:35:07,516 --> 00:35:11,722
That can even be found in the most miserable depressions.

396
00:35:12,945 --> 00:35:33,338
And it's found by turning upon the depression as an object to observe, as an object to investigate, to feel, to experience as it is, to see how there's a part of us that wants to get caught up in it, that wants to get depressed about being depressed, wants to get really angry about it.

397
00:35:34,347 --> 00:35:43,820
That will simply spiral us downwards into the warm hands of Prozac.

398
00:35:43,840 --> 00:35:44,981
That's not the way out, is it?

399
00:35:45,563 --> 00:35:51,911
So we have to be able to lift ourselves up above these moods and make them an object.

400
00:35:51,931 --> 00:35:52,813
Be interested in them.

401
00:35:54,155 --> 00:35:59,282
And the core interest is where and how does suffering arise?

402
00:36:01,806 --> 00:36:03,949
Where's the core of our suffering?

403
00:36:06,139 --> 00:36:13,929
So having dealt now with the more obvious hindrances, we have to deal with, as it were, the more subtle ones.

404
00:36:15,391 --> 00:36:21,978
And those are simply to get caught up in what is beautiful, what is coming up as beautiful in the mind.

405
00:36:22,840 --> 00:36:28,266
Be very careful that once you get into this lovely state of passati, tranquility,

406
00:36:28,465 --> 00:36:31,750
where the mind is still, lovely and peaceful, you see.

407
00:36:32,050 --> 00:36:37,458
If you don't watch it, just very slowly, you wander off into the land of lotus eaters.

408
00:36:38,760 --> 00:36:42,085
And what you've lost is your intelligence.

409
00:36:42,105 --> 00:36:48,635
And you can often tell a meditator that gets into that, their head goes like that.

410
00:36:48,715 --> 00:36:49,735
Very gentle.

411
00:36:50,117 --> 00:36:52,079
Now, if you were to ask them, are they awake?

412
00:36:52,219 --> 00:36:52,860
Of course they're awake.

413
00:36:53,981 --> 00:36:55,704
They're right there, not a problem.

414
00:36:56,072 --> 00:36:56,934
See?

415
00:36:56,954 --> 00:36:59,516
But the intelligence has switched off.

416
00:36:59,536 --> 00:37:02,079
They've just sunk into that lovely state of tranquility.

417
00:37:03,019 --> 00:37:03,820
What a waste of time.

418
00:37:05,081 --> 00:37:10,367
Instead, this is the perfect opportunity to really go into the breath.

419
00:37:11,327 --> 00:37:12,710
To center in on the breath.

420
00:37:13,010 --> 00:37:15,112
To go for the very center of the breath.

421
00:37:15,492 --> 00:37:24,021
And as you beeline in, focus in, right into the center of the breath, all that energy will come up to support your investigations.

422
00:37:25,114 --> 00:37:27,858
And you're moving deeper and deeper into concentration.

423
00:37:28,039 --> 00:37:31,782
Deeper and deeper into a direct viewing of things.

424
00:37:31,802 --> 00:37:34,206
So don't waste those moments of tranquility.

425
00:37:34,626 --> 00:37:35,288
Acknowledge them.

426
00:37:35,387 --> 00:37:36,048
Very beautiful.

427
00:37:36,648 --> 00:37:40,554
But really work to put your mind right into the center of the breath.

428
00:37:40,875 --> 00:37:43,498
Awaken that question mark.

429
00:37:43,518 --> 00:37:43,838
You see?

430
00:37:44,199 --> 00:37:45,740
And keep going into the center.

431
00:37:47,242 --> 00:37:48,284
Why into the center?

432
00:37:48,543 --> 00:37:49,806
Because of the focus.

433
00:37:50,190 --> 00:37:57,202
And when something comes to take you out of the focus of the breath, that very same focus moves to that new object.

434
00:37:58,204 --> 00:38:02,251
Whether it be a pain in the leg or a sound of a bird, it doesn't matter.

435
00:38:02,552 --> 00:38:04,416
It'll just shift like that and then come back.

436
00:38:05,056 --> 00:38:06,418
It'll stay with you all the time.

437
00:38:08,262 --> 00:38:15,034
So don't waste those times in our meditation when the peace descends upon us.

438
00:38:21,358 --> 00:38:35,956
One of the misunderstandings perhaps, that's not the word I'm looking for, is this business of self-awareness.

439
00:38:37,798 --> 00:38:44,768
When we're self-aware, when we're aware of being an observer, you see, there's still a shuddering in the mind.

440
00:38:45,405 --> 00:38:58,909
What's happening is that this consciousness, looking into the mind, feeling what's in the heart, sensing what's in the body, being aware of it, being with it, is also, as it were, catching its own image in the mind.

441
00:39:00,393 --> 00:39:04,039
You've watched TV, where you can see yourself watching TV.

442
00:39:04,119 --> 00:39:34,059
it's exactly that and your attention is moving from you watching TV in the TV to watching the TV however as the program gets more interesting the attention suddenly blocks onto the program and you don't see yourself in the screen watching yourself watching TV so that's the trick you see if that sense of observer is there you just note it self-awareness just keep coming back to the object and it will block it

443
00:39:35,440 --> 00:39:44,952
Alternatively, if there's a lot of peace around, if there's a lot of tranquility and the sense of self comes up like that, turn upon the self.

444
00:39:45,853 --> 00:39:49,838
Find out where does that image of a self arise.

445
00:39:51,880 --> 00:39:52,722
Where's it come from?

446
00:39:53,181 --> 00:39:54,543
Where's it being manufactured?

447
00:39:57,807 --> 00:40:02,494
Now, the final thing is this whole business of prioritizing.

448
00:40:03,284 --> 00:40:17,782
In terms of meditation, we can't prioritize any part of the day, because all parts of the day are absolutely equally important in the process of growing awareness, of growing intelligence, and of growing effort.

449
00:40:18,402 --> 00:40:22,507
So don't say to ourselves, the sitting is more important than the walking.

450
00:40:23,449 --> 00:40:25,831
The walking is more important than the eating.

451
00:40:26,268 --> 00:40:30,523
Eating is more important than opening a door, walking up the stairs or having a pee.

452
00:40:30,543 --> 00:40:30,884
It's not.

453
00:40:31,005 --> 00:40:35,400
It all has to be equally seen as absolutely important.

454
00:40:36,831 --> 00:40:39,155
There mustn't be a break in that continuity.

455
00:40:39,454 --> 00:40:46,704
And what we're going for is a continuous state of awareness, a continuous state of presence all the way through the day.

456
00:40:47,666 --> 00:40:51,329
And so you have to see, first of all, those wrong opinions.

457
00:40:51,771 --> 00:40:54,393
And secondly, you have to see what parts of the day are weak.

458
00:40:54,934 --> 00:40:55,775
When do we give in?

459
00:40:55,976 --> 00:40:57,097
When do we stop, you see?

460
00:40:57,878 --> 00:40:59,440
Those are the parts you have to empower.

461
00:41:00,001 --> 00:41:03,666
When you empower those parts, you empower the whole day.

462
00:41:04,050 --> 00:41:10,019
So our commitment is moment to moment mindfulness, so long as there's wakefulness.

463
00:41:21,297 --> 00:41:31,594
So, what I suggest is that you draw a line, you see, and just take a moment to recommit yourself to the practice.

464
00:41:33,041 --> 00:41:38,050
And every day you should draw that line and recommit yourself to the practice.

465
00:41:38,990 --> 00:41:40,934
That commitment is the aditan.

466
00:41:41,173 --> 00:41:44,559
It's the determination to go on.

467
00:41:44,579 --> 00:41:48,525
And that determination has to be renewed every so often.

468
00:41:48,965 --> 00:41:55,235
And the best thing to do is to always choose a point of the day when you make this very firm commitment to the practice.

469
00:41:55,822 --> 00:41:58,447
And it's something that you can take with you in daily life.

470
00:41:58,967 --> 00:42:00,530
It's not just something that we do here.

471
00:42:01,130 --> 00:42:10,905
You can take it right into your daily life as one point in the day when you argue yourself, if you don't feel like it, to commit yourself to a moment-to-moment mindfulness.

472
00:42:12,708 --> 00:42:23,704
So, I'd like to bring this little talk to an end by allowing you just for a moment there to draw up your will, the Dhamma Chaitanya, the will...

473
00:42:24,409 --> 00:42:34,170
for the noble truth, translated later into the Mahayana system as the Bodhicitta, the mind bent on enlightenment.

474
00:42:34,190 --> 00:42:44,190
So commit yourself, and I will draw this little talk to an end with an offering of a blessing to you from the three Buddhas.

475
00:42:56,050 --> 00:43:09,030
sābhā buddhā balāpātā pachekānāṁ ca yambalāṁ ārahantanāṁ tathējena rakhaṁ paṇḍāmi sābhāso

